## CHANGE MANAGEMENT RULES

These rules exist because this codebase is maintained by a non-coder via AI tooling. Safety
is more important than elegance.

1. SCOPE LOCK. Only change what was explicitly asked. If you notice something else worth
   improving, mention it at the end. Do not fix it silently.

2. NO SILENT REFACTORS. Never rename variables, reorganize structure, or change function
   signatures unless that was the explicit request.

3. COMPLETE FILES ONLY. Deliver complete, deploy-ready files, never diffs or partial
   snippets, unless explicitly asked. Files go straight from output into the repo via
   GitHub Desktop. Syntax-check before delivering (node --check where applicable).

4. PRESERVE LINE ENDINGS. This is a Windows environment. Preserve CRLF line endings on every
   file. Do not silently convert to LF.

5. NO EM DASHES. Em dashes are banned everywhere, including code comments and generated copy.
   Use a colon, a comma, or a hyphen instead.

6. EXPLAIN THE DIFF. For any change to sd-scoring.js, recommendation-roles.js, or sd-app.js,
   include a plain-English explanation of exactly what changed and why, written for someone
   who does not code.

7. FLAG BLAST RADIUS. If a change to one file requires a change in another to stay
   consistent, call it out explicitly before proceeding. Do not make the secondary change
   silently.

8. STATIC PAGE REGENERATION. If you edit resort data in resorts.js or change a page template,
   remind the operator to re-run the relevant generators:
     node generate-mountain-pages.mjs
     node generate-state-pages.mjs
     node generate-city-pages.js
   and, if scoring files changed, to re-run obfuscate-scoring.mjs, then redeploy via
   GitHub Desktop.

9. TEST THE CRITICAL PATH. After any scoring or UI change, the operator should manually test:
   load homepage, enter a day, verify the Top Pick and the other three roles each show a
   resort whose assigned role matches what its actual score says.

